value.value: In context it makes a bit more sense, given the family dynamic she’s coming from. There are plenty of trans women who don’t play that game-I don’t wear makeup and my wardrobe would probably be best described as “functional”. But, with that said, it’s a very dangerous world for most trans women. Oftentimes “prettying up” is the only way to pass, and passing is the best way to minimize danger. Trans celebrities, what few there are, so not represent the ground-level reality of most trans folks’ lives, and it’s dangerous to use someone like Caitlyn or Laverne Cox as an “example” if how most trans women are.

Also just to point something out about another reply to your comment, many times trans women are caught between two overlapping bad things. We’re expected not to “reinforce the gender binary” by being too pretty or feminine, but we also are pressured to conform be society in general and by medical gatekeepers in particular. If we’re too pretty we’re “deceptive” and probably deserve the bad things that happen to us, and if we aren’t pretty enough then we’re “pathetic” and “deluded”, which is used to undermine our gender identity. There’s a loooot to unpack when it comes to passing, history, society, and trans folks’ place in feminism.

value.value: She skyrocketed at the beginning of her career. Her very first Rolling Stone cover was the shot of a nude John Lennon in bed, next to a fully clothed Yoko Ono. It was brilliant. (and if I remember correctly, John died either that very day or shortly thereafter. It’s the last picture of him taken before he was murdered).

For many many years, Leibovitz was the best female portrait shooter in the world. Her concepts, composition, art direction - just unparalleled. But the past decade (or more) her work has really fallen off. Her VF pieces are just wide crowd shots photoshopped together (not always, mind) with perhaps a color theme to tie it together. It’s like she’s phoning it in these days. In fact, some of her group shots have awkward arm/leg juxtapositions that are absolutely amateur-level mistakes.
If you check out her early work, you’d be stunned how workaday her portfolio has become.
